segments.text: we felt, at least I felt, that the public was not turned off on veterinary medicine, but they wasn't turned off.
Yeah, just didn't.

You know, they kind of accepted, you know, I got a vet down the street to treat my dog, but I doubt if we really, I don't think that we were appreciated in the proportions of what veterinarians sacrificed
and getting the kind of education that they were beginning to get at that time.
It was an expensive, long-term thing, highly scientific type thing.
I appreciated that because I made a point to understand how these graduates are, what they're going through.
So I really don't think the public, per se, really put the veterinarian up on a high plane.
What we were struggling to do, excuse me,
I think I might have thought in my heart that our image was 100% about love veterinarians, but I don't think they did, and I still don't think they did, and I don't think they do.
But I think they have a great deal of respect, and I think enough to where the veterinary profession will survive on their reputation, because I think they've become better accepted.
You have to look at veterinary medicine as one of those things that when you spend money with somebody,
That's not the most pleasant thing.
So I guess everybody, every type of practitioner, dentist, everybody else has got that little barrier there.
But I think through some of the things that have been done, and hopefully I have a part of it, did improve the image and did make the veterinary more.
to make people more aware of what they could do and the fact that they have as good an education as you can get.
It's much harder to be a veterinarian in this position sometimes as far as getting into a school.
I think people appreciate that.
Do you think there was a tendency in post-World War II Texas, et cetera, to associate a veterinarian with rural farm pastimes?
Absolutely.
The veterinarian that came out of Texas A&M in 1950 and went to Houston, I can assure you he had a big selling job to do to make a living in that town, which must have been half the size it is today.
But I mean, it was a very risky situation for a man to go to Houston in 1950 instead of practice, hoping they'd have enough pet owners that would appreciate the fact that their pets needed care.
You know, the money in things began to pick up, too.
People had more spendable income after that time.
But to get back to your story, I think it was the image of veterinarian was the old general practitioner that pulled calves and... And we don't need him anymore.
Right, yeah, I mean, I think it was that way.
For a while, I could see where that could have developed.
And I guarantee you, the first one I ever saw, I'll never forget him.
My daddy used him to throw in some hogs.
You know, he was one of those guys who worked
18 hours a day, several days a week, and he had a pretty darn cool facility operation.
Most of them operated out of the pickup or out of an old hole in the wall.
And posted all the animals down at the jump yard.
Posted all the animals down at the...
But anyway, yeah.
Well, in that same token, could you comment broadly on the...

I'd say the income, et cetera, of veterinarians, and also what the new competition of more and more vets in business was doing to income levels, et cetera, prices, competition within the profession, this kind of thing.
I'm not sure, again, what I'm asking, except that how well are vets doing after World War II?
And how are they doing now?
And what's been the big problem economically for them?
I really think the veterinarian always made more money than, let's say, the graduate we went into, let's say,
teaching or something like that.
Okay, that's a good index.
In other words, they're probably doing better than the teacher or the county agent, say.
Yeah, the county agent.
They're working hard.
I would say they were doing, I hate to use percentage figures, I would say they were doing 20-30% better than what you could earn on a salary.
So they're getting a professional income.
Right.
And of course they had some overhead and some risk.
And one of the good things that happened
The veterinarians, through their investing in the real estate, also reap a side benefit.
One in Houston soon found that the location of clinics in certain places is a good investment.
In other words, they can make it go, they can hold on to it and make a living or maybe hire somebody to run it.
But more importantly, it might be worth more in development as development.
or in a good place where it would be brought out for a shopping center.
That wasn't necessarily nearly as true, of course, and probably not at all true in the rural communities.
But some of them did accumulate some pretty fine buildings and some pretty good equipment and some good locations.
And some of them, you know, accumulated some land with them in the case of the rural practitioners and kind of mid-city type people.
Yeah, I would say the veterinarian always did better, and there was always a little bit of professional jealousy, I think, between the professional agriculturist and the professional veterinarian.
Oh, and that could have been part of it.
I think it might have been.
But I would say the veterinarian was always, you know, he worked hard, had a good location, good attitude, good management, good support from his
family and his staff, you know, he always did okay.
But they're hard workers.
They open that door every morning at 6.30 and they close it every night at 6.30 or 5.30 or whatever.
So you have to know that they're working probably 20, 30 percent harder and a lot harder and more hours, 20, 30 percent more hours.
But they had their own business and they had incentives there being in their business.
Okay, now in the 60s or in the boom period, when you start producing 100 new vets a year, what's happening to the income levels?
I think the income level came right on.
It'll hold because of growth in society, affluent.
You know, on the dollars that we had in the late 60s and early 70s, let's use a comparison and don't hold me to it as an actual, but let's say a person in the late 60s and early 70s
was grossing, let's say, $20,000.
I mean netting $20,000 out of a hospital.
Maybe he grossed $100,000, $75,000, whatever it takes.
But he was netting a bit.
I think by the middle 70s and the early 80s that you were talking about $35,000, $70,000 and on up.
But the dollars changed.
Yeah, sure.
I would say...
I would say that there were not very many veterinarians that were not netting $35,000, $40,000 in the years that, in the latter years, I was there, in the late 70s, early 80s.
I would say that there were plenty of them netting a whole lot more than that.
Yeah, well, that's a good index.
A hundred grand, and there were a lot of large animal practitioners that worked hard, that had people working for them.
Of course, you had a lot of the multiple practices started coming in.
You're talking about the expansion?
Yeah.
Other students?
Well, that also was reflected in the multiple practice situation.
You had a guy that was one veterinarian at one location.
Suddenly there was two veterinarians.
Suddenly there was three veterinarians.
Doing different things, servicing different groups.
Or sometimes the veterinarians were going and putting in a satellite clinic.
And it's the best thing that happened in Houston.
It happened in a lot of larger towns.
And then there was another concept that came along that helped.
And that is the concept of the emergency clinics.
After hours clinic.
A lot of those people were absorbed into that time and still are many.
A city like San Antonio, Houston might have a half a dozen emergency clinics for people after hours to go to.
And so those people were absorbed in that county.
It was a new concept in veterinary service in the, started about, I guess, early mid-70s.
You never, ever saw a veterinary emergency clinic.
No, I never even heard of it.
But lately I've been watching and I see them.
Yeah.
Yeah.
And it's a good concept.
It's a good service.
And it's another way to absorb some practitioners.
Now, when a young vet comes out of A&M, has there been any change in how they go into business?
Say, in the early 60s when you started out, were most of these people just hanging out at their shingle?
Or were they associating themselves with someone already in practice?
And did that change over time?
I think you saw a lot of shoestring operations where people just...
they opened up with a mental amount of capital and kind of holding a wall type of concept.
But I think you saw that change between, let's say, 65 and certainly by 1980, that the veterinarians, young veterinarians, were willing to take more risk.
In other words, they went and they borrowed big money from big financial... Set up, okay.
And set up, a lot of times, almost immediately went into their own freestanding buildings.
Of course, Houston, the largest city,
You couldn't do that near Muscovy, but you could always get in the shopping center or a strip center or something like that.
And some of them went into these kind of things.
But you didn't see, oh, you saw a few that went to the cities in those 50s and 60s time, and some of them before my time, but I can see what they did after I came.
Put in their own freestanding buildings, very small buildings, looking for location more than anything.
And then they added to them.
They added associates, and they added partners.
You find people that started a partnership that broke away from each other.
This one went to this part of town.
This one went to large animal only.
This one went to small animal only.
These kind of partnerships you saw.
And then all it did was just multiply itself because there again you get another clinic, another practitioner serving another clientele.
And he adds people, veterinarians to his business.
It's a little smaller.
A good example of that is Tremere's.
Tremere's practice.
He used to be associated in general practice when they went in in the 50s.
You know, everybody was a general practitioner.
Sure, yeah, did everything.
If you didn't go to Houston or Dallas, you were a general practitioner.
See, and I had a talk at that luncheon, at that academy luncheon, with a guy in Dallas, I believe.
I should have brought my list with me, but he's a heart specialist, I believe.
And he has four or five specialists with him, and that's all they do.
They service, apparently, the other clinics.
Well, that was another concept that came along after the middle 70s was the specialty surgery kind of thing, specialty dermatology clinics, and these kind of things.
And they'd get referrals, like you say.
Take the average practitioner that just didn't have the equipment nor perhaps the expertise to do back surgery on a dog.
Well, Herman Dietrich comes to my mind.
He went into specialty surgery.
Very brilliant person.
And I
You know, he kind of had his own little ego, but he could do anything with surgical procedures.
Very respected.
In fact, he burned out just being a dog and cat doctor.
That was below his intelligence, and I don't mean that complimentary.
Yeah, I understand.
So he and then we had other people went into dermatology and heart work, and I'm sure there's some I'm missing out on that we also found.
The general practitioner began to become a specialist too.
We had people who still do.
They make circuits.
They go on berries in Wise County, another one in Parker County, another one in Wichita County.
Their home base might be in San Antonio.
Let me ask you a couple of other general questions about the development of the, you might say, the vet economy.
One is, did you see, or had it already occurred, a balance, a change in the balance, let's say, between large animal and small animal practice or income into the profession between 65 and 83?
Was it marked?
Oh, very definitely.
I think you just have to say that, and the way you prove that up is that, you know, when you look at the graduates, where do they go?
Okay, I'll get those statistics.
That's a good thing to pursue.
I've had a practitioner tell me, and he built a special place that people come and intern with him in his general practice in South Texas.
And he built a dormitory type thing at his clinic where people come and stay at his expense of housing them.
And the intern, he tells me that some years he doesn't get a call.
People are going into it.
other types of practice, and there's nothing wrong with those kind of practices.
Small animal, they want to go to the city, they want to go to the country, they want to go to specialty practices, they want to go to teaching, research, and that sort of thing.
So I think you've seen, I bet if you put a reading on it, you probably can tell by looking at association records, I wouldn't be surprised if it was certainly at least two-thirds, one-third.
I think it's two-thirds small animal and one-third other.
Okay.
And a pretty good index of that is simply where they're domiciled.
In other words, those people in the city are going to be small animals, basically.
That's right.
You'll see some GPs there.
Sure.
Horse people.
Yeah.
And you'll see it'll be mostly small animals because the population pretty well dictates what professions go where.
Yeah.
There's more venison here than there are in Austin, if you might look at the numbers.
But, yeah.
It is, and it is a considerable problem.
I think there's still an adequate number of general practitioners, you know.
The rancher may not think that, but, you know, a general practitioner's got to get over here, too.
Yeah, sure.
And he works hard.
He's got to do it over hours.
So, you know, you like to have one on every elbow when you want it.
Yeah, right.
That cost, too.
Now, in that same general line, in the changing complexion of the profession, let's say, women are coming in when you start out.
How has this affected or impacted on the income levels and profiles?
The reason I ask is I've heard some grousing.
Well, you know, I've been away from it for about five, six years now.

I don't know if it's like it was then, but let me tell you what I sensed at the time, and I think it's probably a true thing, that even though you've got 50% of the graduates that are women, you know, you don't necessarily have that reflected in practice.
No, it's not.
That's right.
Most of them are not what you call the...
owner-manager type situation.
They work for somebody else, they have husbands, and they have secondary income for the family.
And also, that also reflected in the participation in the professional association.
I could sense that we were not getting the women into the association numbers that we were getting the men in.
One reason was that they were not the part
and that they worked for other people.
They were not on the salaries that made the income maybe that some of their peers did.
And I sensed that.
And I think if you look at the membership and the attrition that they've had with the graduates in the last 10 years, you'd see that.
I haven't looked at it, but I think you might.
But see, there's another side of that too.
The fact that there are 50% women graduating out of the class
it doesn't overrun the profession quite as strongly as if they were all men.
That's right.
Okay, so you're getting a lot more bodies out there, but really less product or competition or whatever you want to call it.
You're not near the numbers of practitioners that it would be if they were all male.
Now, that's based on my experience.
It's based on a little bit of philosophy.
Yeah, well, I was curious about that because I've heard, well, one side of it was that
Women are coming out and competing, and they're not setting up shop, and they don't have all these expenses, and they're, in effect, flooding the market or something.
You know, that was the implication.
But what you're saying is really totally different, in a way.
I think that's true.
I'm sure there's some of the other that goes on, too.
Well, let's face it, if we could get good women to come in and practice long hours just like the men, I mean, I have no problem with that philosophically or anything else.
But I think, as a practical matter, it just doesn't work in the same proportion.
The women working in this particular gate, the men in another one, have different motivations, different demands.
Let's face it, my wife doesn't make as much money as I do, but she has a job.
It's very important that you have one.
And I think that's going to be true, and the woman veterinarian, she may not make, and I don't think there's much in the plan to go in and be a preparer.
So that would be the key in the difference.
I'm going to.
I'm going to follow up on all this with Grinchow and Al Price and so forth.
Because I think it's interesting.
I think this is kind of some of the key to understanding what's going on in the world.
And hopefully the book will be of some value to people because we can at least expose these questions.
I don't want to answer them.
Well, I think, yeah, right.
Better economics is a very important side of the whole thing.
That's really what we're talking about in a sense.
But it's very interesting to be able to see what I've been able to see.
Well, the nice thing about you right now, and that's why I was so anxious to get with you early on, is now you can step back and look at it from a different perspective.
When you're in the middle of it, your world view is not the same at all.
Be more objective.
That's right.
But it's a good profession.
It's one that I enjoyed being with when I was there.
Well, I would think so.
And I would think, again, that the public estimation of veterinary medicine is probably going to increase.
I think under the influence of, call it what you will, environmentalism, conservation, all that kind of thing, really does have an animal-human dimension to it.
And that could be worked to the advantage of the profession.
Let me tell you another consideration.
You look at the young married couples right now.
that are coming up, and they have a very, very, very much higher regard for their pets and their animals than they did a guy that's my age now that's middle-aged.
Oh yeah, when I came out, man, we wouldn't spend a nickel on an animal because it's not worth it.
You can go get another one.
Yeah, that's right.
But I tell you what, the daughters and sons that I raised, don't you think that they're going to let those animals suffer?
There's two things for it, that they were brought up, I think, in caring families that stressed, you know, and the school stressed the human treatment of animals and things like that.
And animal became sort of a, as you say, a bond to the human side of things.
You've got an appreciation for that.
And, of course, people have dollars to spend that we didn't have, you know, at that time.
But you've got a different public out there now.
You've got a different clientele.
I think that's going to certainly work in the favor of the practitioner.
It doesn't necessarily reflect itself in the general practitioner, because it's a game of economics with cattle and animals and even horses that are traded in commerce and hogs.
So you can't quite put that same thing on it.
But let me say this.
The people that are carrying those animals, horses, cattle, hogs,
a much more fluent society too.
They know that there are things in science that can be done to animals that maybe my daddy didn't appreciate.
God bless him, he was struggling.
He ate kids.
Perhaps even myself.

Let me ask you some, I'm going to close you out pretty soon, I know you're getting tired, but several other dimensions of that practice, I guess, is what would you say were some of the major problems that you sensed confronting the industry?
The profession you mean?
Yeah, the profession.
While I was there, you mean?
Yeah.
Or even today, just random ideas.
Well, of course, I always think of the things that we did and the things we reacted to.
Of course, you know, education was one of those things we tried to help solve through the academy.
We also fought real hard to keep another veterinary school from being put in the state of Texas Tech.
Okay, why did you fight it?
We fought it because of two things.
One, we didn't think that the state would be willing over the long haul to support two quality institutions in Texas.
And I tell you what, if we had those two right now, we'd be hurting, because I understand the Texas A&M is serving for money right now.
In fact, they might even be on probation if they don't get some more money for certain things that they need to do down there.
But that was, of course, and I guess we may have had some selfish motives, too.
Everybody thought, well, you know, we don't need that many more veterinarians.
We've already...
expanded at A&M to a trimester system.
We're already doubling the enrollment.
Of course, we did that in the face of threat.
I don't think we would have doubled the enrollment if we'd been rocking long, free, and easy on what was going on.
That's a good thing, and I know this is kind of a sensitive area, I guess.
Does the TVMA... What kind of relationship do you have with the vet school in terms, say, of...
of influencing decisions relating to admissions, etc.
Well, you know, I'd be quite right.
The medical association has always thought of as controlling admission to medical schools as essentially a sort of a union card.
Do you sense that at all?
Well, I think we certainly have that impression that that association had a lot of influence on the card.
I think they listened to us a lot.
Well, I have to give Al Price credit for the fact that he ran a pretty tight ship.
He set up standards that you couldn't penetrate.
You know, I mean, it wasn't this old, good old boy, you know, I'm going to get your boy in where he's qualified.
Not that thing.
I bet that pressure would be big.
We're going to quit teaching this, and we're going to start teaching that.
He, you know, give him credit for that, and I think that has carried on.
I think they've built a good, solid reason to say, you know, these are things that are good for teaching.
Professions should support these things.

Of course, Dave, I think when the profession says, and the association says, well, we need more emphasis on equine medicine, more emphasis on felon medicine, or more emphasis on specialization, teaching small animal practitioners to do more of this and less of that, we need more
on veterinary economics about how to run a practice.
I think they're sensitive to things like that.
Boy, I think they still need that, don't they?
Aren't they beginning to move in that direction a little bit?
Yeah, I don't think it'd be hard to overdo that.
Of course, the cricket is always full of time.
Yeah, I know, they don't have time.
But, you know, one limiting factor, and I think most veterinarians will admit, that they're not really natural-born business people.
No, they're not.
Most doctors are not, period.
They don't have a good staff or a good wife or a good somebody to come in there and tell them how much you're spending and how much you're bringing in.
They're never so busy out here hitting the road or doing surgery that they don't know what's going on.
I'm going to follow that up because that's a good opportunity for both business and medical and...
That practice is to work out a program.
We don't have that program.
I teach economic and business history.
That's why I'm kind of interested in that.
Oh, do you?
You still teach some?
Yeah.
So I'm kind of interested in that.
That's one thing I wanted to do that I got lost in the business profession.
I never get back to get a master's degree to do some teaching.
Never too late.
It's kind of hard, but it's never too late.
So...
Would you comment just again in very broad terms on your relations with the A&M School of Veterinary Medicine?
Well, you know, Henry, I took on probably a little bit different image than maybe the guy that succeeded me or maybe even the guy that's there now.
You know, A&M was my school.
Okay, yeah, sure.
And I roomed with veterinarians when I went to school.
I had a national appreciation for that in my agricultural background.
But, you know, I broke my back to do everything I could.
In fact,
You know, I was there when we created the Veterinary Medical Diagnostic Laboratory.
Okay.
That's another one of the legislative things that we did during my tenure.
Yeah, that's a good point.
And I felt so good about it because, first of all, my people needed it, and I was doing something for my school.
Yeah.
And I guess I'm a little sentimental about that.
But, you know, I would do anything for the veterinary school and Texas A&M.
It was natural.
Yeah, okay.
But I'll tell you, there was a mutual respect in those guys.
They respected what I was trying to do.
I certainly respected them.
I called shots on them.
And so consequently, it was kind of romantic.
Yeah.
And would you say that still holds, pretty much?
Well, you know, I don't know.
Like I said, after I left, I think different people have different feelings.
I'm sort of a sentimental person.
But I still think,
that they know the importance of veterinary school.
They've got to go in and input as much as they can and support the school through the association, with the association, vice versa.
And I don't know how much of that continues, but I know it has to be.
It just has to be.
But that's the way you get things done.
It's cooperation.
I couldn't sense or see any problems or think of anything, but I was just wondering.
I don't know either, and I certainly wasn't that way when I was there.
I'm hoping.
I don't think it would be a very, very serious problem on any dean's part to completely ignore the profession and association that represents it.
And it would certainly be stupid on the part of the association not to understand the real need and what the college is doing to support everything that they possibly can.
We're in this thing together.
Yeah, absolutely.
I'll follow that up with Price, too.
I've always liked him.
He'll tell me the way it is.
I have a feeling.
I guarantee.
Okay, so general problems I was concerned with and your relationships with the veterinary medicine schools, school of veterinary medicine.
Okay, what about relationships with other state associations and organizations that are somewhat in your ballpark?
Right.
Well, we always were brought together in that area because the American Veterinary Association always brought the constituent associations in every so often to talk about what the AVMA was doing.
Of course, we had separate memberships and the views were not, it wasn't a federation type.
Yeah.
And at that time, we also got our different state executives together to kind of talk over our own little problem.
We had an aid for that where we
sit down and talk about running associations.
Did you usually go to the AVMA meetings?
Always.
Did a pretty good delegation go with you usually, or from Texas?
Well, you know, we went to two different groups, Henry.
I would go to a constituent meeting where they were strictly talking what AVMA was trying to do in the past.
And then we would go to the annual convention where we were trying to get
ABMA to do what our particular state wanted them to do.
We took a delegation there.
We'd always take two voting delegates and the president.
And I would go along and kind of advise on the resolution that we were trying to pass.
We were always interested in the way that the ABMA distributed its voting weight of its vote.
compared to numbers.
We were always on the short end of the stick.
We had more numbers and less weight.
You voted two delegates, although our region might have had three times the numbers they had in New England.
So we were always fighting for things like that.
And we were fighting for things that the council, the various councils were doing.
They had counsel on everything, from small animal medicine to specialty practices.
We were always trying to get them into things that were
You know, we were into it.
Did you have any formal or informal affiliations with some of the breeder associations in Texas, say, or just general American breeder associations?
Cattle or whatever?
Not really.
You know, usually we were invited to, but I was invited.
That could be burdensome, I guess, after all.
Texas Southwestern Cattle Records, for instance.
They always invited me and my friends to their annual meeting.
The Texas Farm Bureau, they would invite me since I was a former employer, they used to invite me.
Did you go?
Oh, yes.
I go very frequently.
I always have one every time.
Did you tend to use the Farm Bureau, for example, as a forum for promulgating what veterinary medicine was...
doing at all?
Did you have that opportunity?
Well, not really, but I think we always kept, it was an ear, you know.
What we did more than that, and I got into it long towards the end of my career with the association, that we met with what they call the Texas Agricultural Council.
Okay.
Every commodity group that is in the state, plus that's all your cattle raisers, and they weren't breeding groups, they were commodity groups.
Yeah.
Cattle people, grain people, cotton people, milk people, you name it.
We still have that.
I was not as active in veterinary medicine, but I began to get into it because I realized that we had to have the agricultural community aware of what we're doing.
That was the thing that almost wrecked the practice act last time.
The agricultural community became suspicious that veterinary medicine was trying to encroach on some areas that they'd always thought was their territory.
Embryo transfer.
Pregnancy testing.
And actually and truly, when they rewrote the Practice Act, we had people in the agriculture community.
By that time, I was over in the agriculture community.
I was out of the veterinary community.
You know, attacking their Practice Act in areas that had always been covered in the Practice Act.
So I convinced the agriculture community that, you know, why don't you look at what they're trying to change that encroaches
but let's leave alone the things that they've already got.
I mean, that's not, to me, that's being a little bit picky.
You know, we can kill them.
Our community can kill them on anything we want it to.
You've got the clout.
I said, let's leave the practice act alone, except in those areas that they're trying to go into that we feel like we question, or that we have a right to input on.
And consequently, I think I was kind of the peacemaker, even though
There were a few that knew this, and I wouldn't try to make it public.
But I didn't get paid for it.
I didn't ask for it.
But I had enough respect for the people.
Well, that makes your world easier, too.
I had enough respect for the people that were trying to do this because they were my former leaders.
I had enough respect for their customers to understand their side of the problem.
But I was sort of a mediator, a referee, and I was glad I could play that role.
What about relations with other states?
associations, Oklahoma, Louisiana, et cetera.
For example, when I was raised in Louisiana, every vet came to Texas A&M.
Well, we had a lot closer relation with Louisiana for that reason, because we had quite a few graduates.
So we had joint meetings with Louisiana on a number of occasions.
Oh, is that right?
We met in New Orleans one time.
We met in Houston a couple of times, I believe it was.
But we felt a lot closer to them,
We had a lot of friends.
What was your attitude in opening the vet school in Louisiana?
Were you still involved?
I was here then.
I don't think it was any sentiment.
